"It takes a lot of time to centralise mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, called bariatric surgery, use different methods to reduce the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the ability of the body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have occurred in people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
BMI, a weight measurement unit relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18,5-24,9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate the BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at the General Min-Sheng Hospital in Taiwan used strict data after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of barbaric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy in mansions - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI for subjects with surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 until the end of the fifth year in the study.
In the meantime, BMI remained close to the same level, i.e. 29.
Among those who had surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured at only 1% and partially at only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and "bad LDL cholesterol" "were generally better in the surgical group", the authors concluded.
Researchers have also monitored the blood haemoglobin A1c, which reflects the level of hypoglycaemia in time.
Researchers say that the optimal haemoglobin level of A1c is below 7%.
Following surgery, the mean haemoglobin of A1c decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, approximately 8% remained.
But this improved "glycemic control" - reflected by the improved levels of haemoglobin A1c - did not reduce the rate of mortality to five years, according to researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared with the gastrectomy group in mansions, the bypass surgical intervention group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), reported more significant reductions in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%) and presented a higher probability of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on people with high weight in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, from Arizona University, Phoenix Faculty of Medicine.
In the Swedish study, obese people who had had bariatric surgery presented a probability of dying at about 29% less after 15 years, compared with a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a benefit in survival in patients with surgical intervention, Blackstone said it was an optimistic aspect for people with BMI under 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is the point where this work is critical, because it says that this surgical intervention is safe in the lower BMI group," she said, without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease.
Blackstone added that their patients and doctors should start - take the patient’s BMI seriously when it reaches 27-30.
